1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,000
Conway's Game of Life — HighLife variant (B36/S23)

2
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:14,000
First, the same engine headless in the terminal with the text/ANSI renderer (the Tarea 2 core)

3
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:22,000
Now the real-time viewer: computed and drawn on the GPU via CUDA <-> OpenGL interop, no host copies

4
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:30,500
Strategy-pattern core + a swappable ISimEngine interface (CPU/CUDA/OpenCL)

5
00:00:30,500 --> 00:00:39,000
The GUI is a separate front-end: Qt owns the loop, driving the engine and the present path

6
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:48,000
CudaEngine keeps two device buffers, ping-ponging on the GPU (read A -> write B -> swap)

7
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:56,000
scripts/run_gui.sh uses PRIME offload to put the OpenGL context on the NVIDIA GPU

8
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:02,500
The terminal confirms GL_RENDERER = NVIDIA GeForce GTX 1660 Ti

9
00:01:02,500 --> 00:01:10,000
The title bar reads "CudaEngine / zero-copy interop": the fast path is active

10
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:18,500
At init, the OpenGL PBO is registered with CUDA via cudaGraphicsGLRegisterBuffer (WriteDiscard)

11
00:01:18,500 --> 00:01:27,500
Each frame maps the PBO and copies CUDA's current buffer device->device (cudaMemcpy D2D)

12
00:01:27,500 --> 00:01:36,500
Then glTexSubImage2D streams that PBO into a GL_R8UI texture (1 byte/cell), no host pointer

13
00:01:36,500 --> 00:01:44,000
The data never returns to the host over PCIe — that is exactly what interop saves

14
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:52,500
If the GL context lands on the Intel iGPU, interop fails and gracefully falls back to host-upload

15
00:01:52,500 --> 00:02:00,500
The shaders are GL 3.3 core, read at runtime from src/gui/shaders/

16
00:02:00,500 --> 00:02:09,000
Vertex shader: builds a fullscreen triangle from gl_VertexID — no VBO, no attributes

17
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:17,500
Fragment shader: maps each pixel back to a cell (same center/scale as mouse picking)

18
00:02:17,500 --> 00:02:25,500
It reads the exact cell with texelFetch on a usampler2D: integer texture, no filtering

19
00:02:25,500 --> 00:02:33,000
Binary mode: dead cells dark, live cells in the palette's hot colour

20
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:41,000
Neighbour count: the shader sums the 8 neighbours with texelFetch and colours by density

21
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:49,500
Age heatmap: colours by generations survived, from a second R8UI texture

22
00:02:49,500 --> 00:02:58,500
The "age" lives in a host buffer, +1 per generation, uploaded only in this mode (others pay nothing)

23
00:02:58,500 --> 00:03:07,000
6 palettes in the shader; for age, "spectrum" rotates hue (red->green->blue) instead of brightness

24
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:15,000
Past ~4 px/cell the shader darkens each cell's border: grid lines with no geometry

25
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:23,000
Wheel: zoom keeping the cell under the cursor fixed; middle- or right-drag: pan

26
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:31,500
Left-drag paints live cells, Shift erases, via ISimEngine::pokeCell (live editing)

27
00:03:31,500 --> 00:03:39,500
Each frame presents, then steps: the cell you paint is shown before it evolves

28
00:03:39,500 --> 00:03:46,500
The backends are verified bit-for-bit against the CPU oracle and against Golly/bgolly

29
00:03:46,500 --> 00:03:55,000
Zero-copy interop + shaders: computed and displayed on the GPU, with no host copies
